</style><div class="boxcont last noshadow blkbg debate"><div id="taba" class="tabhead "><h3><a href="javascript:void(0);">FACTOIDS</a></h3></div><div class="clear"></div><div data-tb-region="top-news-tab" id="tab1"><div id="content-1"><ul class="topstr-list gap topmarging"><li> In Delhi, 95 percent women felt unsafe in public spaces. This includes sexual comments or obscene gestures (52 percent), touching (20 percent), stalking (10 percent), and assaulting (0.3 percent)- ICRW study 2012. </li><li> India's sex ratio is one of the lowest worldwide. India has a sex ratio of 943 females per 1000 males, which is just ahead of Pakistan's sex ratio of 942. Most countries and even India's neighbouring countries like Nepal, Sri Lanka and Myanmar show much better sex ratio at 1014, 1032 and 1048 respectively whereas for Bhutan, China and Afghanistan it is lower than India at 897, 927 and 931 respectively.</li><li> 57 percent of girls in India are married by age 18. </li><li> One in five women in India gives birth before reaching age 18. Two in five women in India give birth before reaching age 20. </li><li> Girls and women are the main targets of immoral trafficking in India, making up 76% of human trafficking cases nationwide over a decade, according to NCRB. Over the past five years, only 23% of human-trafficking cases filed ended in conviction.</li><li> A total of 24,771 dowry deaths have been reported in the country in past three years with maximum of them occurring in Uttar Pradesh with 7,048 deaths.</li><li> National Crime Records Bureau (NCRB) statistics for 2014 revealed that in 86% cases of rape the perpetrator is known to the victim. In 2014, figures released by NCRB show that in two percent of all reported case of rape, the alleged offender was a family member. Of the 36739 reported cases, 713 were of incest, with 90 percent of the victims being minors. </li><li> in the "Offenders Relation and Proximity To Rape Victims During 2014" NCRB findings showed that in two percent of the 30077 cases the accused was a father, brother or grandfather." </li><li> Despite recent improvements, under reporting remains a major problem in violence against women. A study in 2014 revealed that most cases of sexual and physical violence against women, whether by their husbands or other men, went unreported. For the year 2005, only about 5.8% of the incidents of sexual violence against women which were committed by men other than the survivors' husbands were reported to the police.</li><li> At least 60 million girls who would otherwise be expected to be alive are "missing" from various populations, mostly in Asia, as a result of sex-selective abortions, infanticide or neglect.</li><li> Overall female literacy rate in India is much lower than that of male literacy rate. The female literacy levels according to the 2011 census are 65.46% whereas the male literacy rate is over 80%.</li><li> According to UIS data for the school year ending in 2013, of a total of 17 milion Out-of-school children of primary school age in India, a staggering 12.5 million were girls. </li><li> As per National Crime Records Bureau (2013), of 106,527 cases of violence against women that made it to Indian courts last year, only 15 resulted in a conviction; 10 resulted in an acquittal, 87 percent remained pending. </li><li> In 2005, the amendment of the Hindu Succession Act gave married and unmarried daughters a right to a share of ancestral land and property equal to that of sons . </li><li> A new study shows that nearly one in ten child deaths under the age of one in India can be attributed to domestic violence against the mother.</li><li> The National Family Health Survey (NFHS) Round III report (2005-06) mentions that in India, one-third of women in the age group 15-49, have experienced physical violence and about one in 10 have experienced sexual violence. In total, 35 per cent women experience physical or sexual violence, 37.2 percent of ever married women have experienced spousal violence.</li><li> On average, in the 100 top companies listed in the Mumbai stock exchange, women constituted 7 percent of all board members and only 5 percent of the senior leadership. Source- Partners in Change 2013. </li><li> In 2014, women occupied only 7 out of 45 Ministerial positions in the Central Council of Ministers, which is a little more than 15% against around 10% women participation in 2004. 62 females have been elected in 2014 Elections constituting more than 11% share in the Lower House. Women form more than 20% of the lower houses in Pakistan, Nepal and China. </li><li> Just one in eight women whose parents own agricultural land inherit any of it.</li><li> Women's contribution to the unpaid care economy of India is worked out to be worth about $38 billion or Rs 1.75 lakh crore. Men contribute only $9.6 billion or about Rs 43,000 crore</li><li> According to statistics from the United Nations, one in five cases of honour killing internationally every year comes from India.</li><li> The female Infant Mortality Rate (IMR) was 42 compared with the male IMR of 39 and the overall IMR of 40 in 2013.</li><li> Overall female literacy rate in India is much lower than that of male literacy rate. The female literacy levels according to the 2011 census are 65.46% whereas the male literacy rate is over 80%. </li><li> As per Census 2011, the highest male literacy rate is in the state of Kerala at 96.1% followed by Lakshadweep a 95.6% and minimum for Bihar (71.2%) & Arunachal Pradesh (72.6%). Female literacy is the maximum for Kerala (92.1%), followed by Lakshadweep (87.9%) and lowest for Bihar (51.5%) & followed by Rajasthan (52.1%). A little more than half of the females are literate in these States.</li><li> There were 2 women judges out of 30 judges in the Supreme Court and there were only 58 women judges out of 609 judges in different High Courts with maximum 25% in Delhi High Court and no women judge in 6 High Courts. </li><li> Only 20.5% women were employed in the organized sector in 2011 with 18.1% working in the public sector and 24.3% in the private. The labour force participation rate for women across all age groups was 25.3 in rural sector and 15.5 in urban sector compared with 55.3 and 56.3 for men in the rural and urban sectors respectively in 2011-12 </li><li> During 2011-12, the average wage received by regular salaried employees of economically active age group was ` 428.66 per day for females compared with ` 550.23 per day for males in rural areas. For urban areas, it was ` 609.7 and ` 805.52 per day for females and males respectively. Most of the Union Territories give the maximum wages in each of the categories.</li><li> Female participation in elections has gone up from 56% in fifteenth General Elections to 66% in the 16th one in 2014. The male participation has also improved from 60% to 67% during the same period.</li></ul></div></div></div><link rel="stylesheet" type="text/css" href="http://itgd-mum-dev-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/others/mediaintoday/indiatoday/mscroller/jquery.mCustomScrollbar.min.css"/><script src="http://itgd-mum-dev-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/others/mediaintoday/indiatoday/mscroller/jquery.mCustomScrollbar.concat.min.js"></script><style>
